{{Infobox language | name = Monguor | altname = Dēd Mongol, Tu | nativename = ''moŋɡuer'' | states = [[China]] | region = [[Qinghai]], [[Gansu]] | speakers = {{sigfig|152,000|2}} | date = 2000 census | ref = e18 | familycolor = Altaic | fam1 = [[Mongolic languages|Mongolic]] | fam2 = Shirongolic | iso3 = mjg | script = [[Latin script]] | glotto = tuuu1240 | glottorefname = Tu | dia1 = Mongghul | dia2 = Mangghuer }}
The '''Monguor language''' ({{zh|s=土族语|p=Tǔzúyǔ}}; also written '''Mongour''' and '''Mongor''') is a [[Mongolic language]] of its Shirongolic branch and is part of the Gansu–Qinghai [[sprachbund]]. There are several dialects, mostly spoken by the [[Monguor]] people. A written script was devised for Huzhu Monguor (Mongghul) in the late 20th century, but has been little used. A division into two languages, namely Mongghul in [[Huzhu Tu Autonomous County]] and Mangghuer in [[Minhe Hui and Tu Autonomous County]], is considered necessary by some linguists. While Mongghul was under strong influence from [[Amdo Tibetan|Tibetan]], the same holds for Mangghuer and [[Chinese language|Chinese]], and local dialects of Chinese such as [[Gangou dialect|Gangou]] were in turn influenced by Monguor.
== Phonology == Monguor has five vowels: /a, e, i, o, u/.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lotpublications.nl/Documents/289_fulltext.pdf|title=Mongolic Phonology and the Qinghai-Gansu Languages|last=Hans|first=Nugteren|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> {| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center" |+Consonants ! colspan="2" | ![[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]] ![[Labiodental consonant|Labiodental]] ![[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ![[Retroflex consonant|Retroflex]] ![[Alveolo-palatal consonant|Alveolo-palatal]] ![[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ![[Velar consonant|Velar]] ![[Uvular consonant|Uvular]] |- ! rowspan="2" |[[Stop consonant|Stop]] !<small>voiceless</small> |p | |t | | | |k | |- ![[Voice (phonetics)|<small>voiced</small>]] |b | |d | | | |g |ɢ |- ! rowspan="2" |[[Affricate consonant|Affricate]] !<small>voiceless</small> | | |t͡s |ʈʂ |t͡ɕ | | | |- ![[Voice (phonetics)|<small>voiced</small>]] | | |d͡z |ɖʐ |d͡ʑ | | | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] | |f |s |ʂ |ɕ | |x | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] |m | |n | | | |ŋ | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | | |l | | |j |w | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Trill consonant|Trill]] | | |r | | | | | |}
==Numerals==
Mongolian numerals such as the following<ref name="Slater">Dpal-ldan-bkra-shis, Slater ''et al.'' 1996: 4</ref> are only in use in the Mongghul dialect, while Mangghuer speakers have switched to counting in Chinese.<ref name="Slater"/> Note that while the Mongolian script has only ''arban'' for 'ten', Middle Mongolian *''harpa/n'' including *''h'' can be reconstructed from the scripts.<ref>Svantesson ''et al.'' 2005: 130</ref> {| class="wikitable" !Numeral !'''Classical Mongolian''' !Monguor |- |1 |nigen |nige |- |2 |qoyar |ghoori |- |3 |ghurban |ghuran |- |4 |dörben |deeran |- |5 |tabun |tawun |- |6 |jirghughan |jirighun |- |7 |dologhan |duluun |- |8 |naiman |niiman |- |9 |yisün |shdzin |- |10 |arban |haran |}
